ce:section.ce:para:
Our experimental design is inspired by the concept of high-intensity gas–liquid reactors using vigorous gas jets, which are known to enhance phase mixing. Wild et al. developed a high velocity impinging stream reactor entering a small reactor volume, moving in a counter-current fashion. Guided by tiny nozzles, gas and liquid feed streams collide in a small reactor volume, resulting in a highly turbulent gas-phase dispersion into the liquid. The mass transfer rate is intensified, supported by bubble formation and breakup. Another design of a high-intensity gas–liquid reactor consists of a pump, an orifice, a vertical tube coaxial to the orifice and an impinging plate. The pump generates a downward vertical liquid jet through the orifice generating gas–liquid dispersion in a tube. The two-phase jet is directed towards an impinging plate near the bottom of the tank and dispersed in the volume of the liquid. The liquid is withdrawn below the impinging plate and recycled [23]. Our experimental design follows the concept of those high-intensity gas–liquid reactors, but we need to simplify it. It would mean having a plasma gas phase over a long length, which is difficult to achieve. Instead, we use a microplasma jet directed towards a liquid (
                        Fig. 2

                        ). We also refrain from flow recycling for repeated gas–liquid interaction, as a single contact will show us better the fundamentals governing the process intensification [24].

To assess the thermal performance of the microplasma and its suitability for process intensification, the thermophysical properties of the argon gas, including density (

                              ρ

                        ), thermal conductivity (k) and heat capacity (cp), were evaluated at operating temperatures ranging from 300 K to 343 K using HYSYS properties. The Peng-Robinson and Uniquac activity coefficient model was used to describe the thermodynamics of the model. An atmospheric feed stream of argon was defined, and a sensitivity analysis was carried out to evaluate the effect of the temperature of the bulk of gas on the thermophysical properties.
